First curl copies the data. Second curl enables the lookup from mongo 
Curls to migrate all sequences to mongo 
{code}
curl -XGET 'http://localhost:8080/restricted/v1/sequence/toMongo?offset=10000&dbTypes=GRL,PARTNER,CLIENT,APPS,PERSISTENT_SEARCH&updateProperty=false'
{code}

{code}
curl -XGET 'http://localhost:8080/restricted/v1/sequence/toMongo?offset=100&dbTypes=GRL,PARTNER,CLIENT,APPS,PERSISTENT_SEARCH&updateProperty=true'
{code}

Migrate specifc sequence to mongo 
{code}
curl -XGET http://localhost:8080/restricted/v1/sequence/toMongoForSequences?offset=100&sequences=POST_ID_SEQ&updateProperty=false
{code}

{code}
curl -XGET http://localhost:8080/restricted/v1/sequence/toMongoForSequences?offset=100&sequences=POST_ID_SEQ&updateProperty=true
{code}

Explanation of the steps for Migration
1.This curl COPIES the data from mysql to mongo with the offset provided. The data is only copied at this point. The sequence look up still happens from mysql
{code}
curl -XGET http://localhost:8080/restricted/v1/sequence/toMongoForSequences?offset=100&sequences=POST_ID_SEQ&updateProperty=false
{code}
2.The data is copied to
{code}
sequenceMongoCon -1
stagingDefault:PRIMARY> db.mongoSequence.findOne();
{
        "_id" : ObjectId("580492d2e4b02dcfbf4c3795"),
        "_class" : "com.spr.utils.core.sequence.beans.MongoSequence",
        "sequenceName" : "POST_ID_SEQ",
        "clientId" : NumberLong(-1),
        "partnerId" : NumberLong(0),
        "name" : "POST_ID_SEQ_0_-1",
        "val" : NumberLong(31850030)
}
{code}
3.When we run the same curl with updateProperty=true, the lookup for the sequence is enabled from mongo. The sequence count starts incrementing from mongo. We can check the sequence that is enabled in mongo from
{code}
stagingDefault:PRIMARY> db.sequenceSettings.find().pretty();
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("5804a6d3e4b02dcfbf4c3fb0"),
    "_class" : "com.spr.utils.core.sequence.beans.SequenceSettings",
    "useMongoForAll" : false,
    "enabledSequences" : {
        "GLOBAL" : [
            "POST_ID_SEQ"
        ]
    }
}
{code}
4.Check the cache refresh for the mongo where lCT is localCacheType
{code}
stagingDefault:PRIMARY> db.cacheRefreshDetails.find(
{'lCT': "SEQUENCE_SETTINGS"}
).pretty();
{ "_id" : ObjectId("5804a6d373390873a58f4635"), "lCT" : "SEQUENCE_SETTINGS", "pId" : NumberLong(0), "sDKey" : "NONE", "uBy" : "10.0.5.198/10.0.5.198_RE_/restricted/v1/sequence/toMongoForSequences", "rD" : ISODate("2016-10-17T10:24:19.904Z") }
{code}
5.This curl COPIES the data from mongo to mysql with the offset provided. The data is only copied at this point. The sequence look up still happens from mongo
{code}
curl -XGET http://localhost:8080/restricted/v1/sequence/toSqlForSequences?offset=1000&sequences=POST_ID_SEQ&updateProperty=false
{code}
6.The data is copied to the SEQUENCE table in mysql
{code}
mysql> select * from SEQUENCE where SEQUENCE_NAME = 'POST_ID_SEQ' \G;
*************************** 1. row ***************************
SEQUENCE_NAME: POST_ID_SEQ
CURRENT_VALUE: 31853776
    INCREMENT: 1
{code}
7. When the toSqlForSequences curl is run with updateProperty=true , the lookup happens from mysql and that sequence is removed from db.sequenceSettings.find().pretty();

STAGING : 
1.Migration was done for POST_ID_SEQ to mongo. The lookup switched to mongo and no issues were seen
2.Migration was done for all sequences to mongo. The lookup switched to mongo and no issues were seen
{code}
stagingDefault:PRIMARY> db.sequenceSettings.find().pretty();
{
	"_id" : ObjectId("5804a6d3e4b02dcfbf4c3fb0"),
	"_class" : "com.spr.utils.core.sequence.beans.SequenceSettings",
	"useMongoForAll" : true,
	"enabledSequences" : {
		"GLOBAL" : [
			"POST_ID_SEQ"
		]
	}
}
{code}
3.Load testing was done and the result is documented here https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1muR48dInlkhhm6GfOdGNBXM-zpzgTOiHVxXbNUH681U/edit#gid=360664004
4.Finally, Migration was done for all sequences to mysql. The lookup switched to mysql and no issues were seen
{code}
stagingDefault:PRIMARY> db.sequenceSettings.find().pretty();
{
	"_id" : ObjectId("5804a6d3e4b02dcfbf4c3fb0"),
	"_class" : "com.spr.utils.core.sequence.beans.SequenceSettings",
	"useMongoForAll" : false,
	"enabledSequences" : {
		
}
{code}
